\begin_layout Enumerate
By definition, any test function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is zero outside of some interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

, and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is continuous and compactly supported means that it has a finite maximum,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\max_{x}|\phi(x)|=\phi_{M}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|f\{\phi\}|=\left|\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\phi(x)dx\right|=\left|\int_{a}^{b}f(x)\phi(x)dx\right|\leq\int_{a}^{b}\left|f(x)\phi(x)\right|dx\leq\phi_{M}\int_{a}^{b}\left|f(x)\right|dx<\infty,
\]

\end_inset

where in the last step we have used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is locally integrable.
 Hence, any locally integrable function defines a distribution, with a finite
 integral for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Solutions:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is bounded in every interval except intervals containing 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, so local integrability is trivial except for intervals containing 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 It is sufficient to consider integrals 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{b}$
\end_inset

, because any interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 can be broken up into 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{0}+\int_{0}^{b}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(-x)=f(x)$
\end_inset

 so we only need to show that the latter is finite.
 But we can now just do the integral explicitly: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{b}\ln x\, dx=\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\int_{\epsilon}^{b}\ln x\, dx=\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\left.x\ln x-x\right|_{\epsilon}^{b}=b\ln b-b,
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}x\ln x=0,
\]

\end_inset

as can easily be seen e.g.
 by L'HÃ´pital's rule applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim\frac{\ln x}{1/x}=\lim\frac{1/x}{-1/x^{2}}=\lim x=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is not locally integrable for intervals containing the origin.
 For example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{b}|g(x)|dx=\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\int_{\epsilon}^{b}\frac{dx}{x}=\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\left.\ln x\right|_{\epsilon}^{b}=\infty.
\]

\end_inset

 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi\}=f\{-\phi'\}$
\end_inset

 is a singular distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We write 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi\}=\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}f'_{\epsilon}\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

, and integrate by parts in 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{\epsilon}\{\phi\}=f_{\epsilon}\{-\phi'\}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f'\{\phi\} & =-\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\left[\int_{-\infty}^{-\epsilon}\underbrace{\ln(-x)}_{u}\underbrace{\phi'(x)dx}_{dv}+\int_{\epsilon}^{\infty}\underbrace{\ln(x)}_{u}\underbrace{\phi'(x)dx}_{dv}\right]\\
 & =-\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\left[\ln(\epsilon)\phi(-\epsilon)-\int_{-\infty}^{-\epsilon}\frac{-1}{x}\phi(x)dx-\ln(\epsilon)\phi(\epsilon)-\int_{\epsilon}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x}\phi(x)dx\right]\\
 & =\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\left[\int_{-\infty}^{-\epsilon}\frac{1}{x}\phi(x)dx+\int_{\epsilon}^{\infty}\frac{1}{x}\phi(x)dx\right]+\cancel{\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}\left[\ln(\epsilon)\left(\phi(\epsilon)-\phi(-\epsilon)\right)\right]}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 In the last line, the first limit is precisely the Cauchy Principal Value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\int g(x)\phi(x)dx$
\end_inset

 (CPV = remove a ball of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 around the singularity, do the integral, and then take the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\to0^{+}$
\end_inset

 limit).
 The second term vanishes because, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 is continuous and infinitely differentiable, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\epsilon)-\phi(-\epsilon)$
\end_inset

 vanishes at least as fast as 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\to0$
\end_inset

, so its product with 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\epsilon$
\end_inset

 vanishes in the limit as in part
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(i).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This last fact is a little subtle.
 Naively, we could just write the Taylor expansion 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)=\phi(0)+\phi'(0)\epsilon+O(\epsilon^{2})$
\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\epsilon)-\phi(-\epsilon)=2\phi'(0)\epsilon+O(\epsilon^{2}).$
\end_inset

 However, it turns out that test functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 are not analytic (do not have a convergent Taylor series) at all
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is differentiable with bounded 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Lipshitz continuous:
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi(x)-\phi(y)|<K|x-y|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 and for some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $K>0$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 you can prove this from the mean-value theorem of analysis), so 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\epsilon)-\phi(-\epsilon)<2K\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and the result follows.
 But I don't expect you to provide this level of proof; a Taylor argument
 is acceptable.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

