\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}g-\omega^{2}g=0$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $-\omega^{2}g=\nabla^{2}g=\frac{1}{r}(rg)''\implies h''=-\omega^{2}h$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h(r)=rg(r)$
\end_inset

.
 The solution to this is 
\begin_inset Formula $h(r)=ce^{i\omega r}+de^{-i\omega r}$
\end_inset

 for some constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r)=\frac{ce^{i\omega r}+de^{-i\omega r}}{r}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

It is a little more tricky to determine whether we should use the 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 term than in class, since both decay at the same rate.
 The ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $c/d$
\end_inset

 will be determined by some kind of boundary condition at infinity, but
 what might this be? It is acceptable for you to just punt on this here;
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\pm i\omega r}$
\end_inset

 are complex conjugates of each other, your analysis will apply equally
 well to either one, and you can arbitrarily pick one, say 
\begin_inset Formula $ce^{i\omega r}/r$
\end_inset

, to analyze.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

However, to see why there should be a sensible choice, recall that this
 operator arose in pset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

5 by assuming a time dependence 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 multiplying the solution, in which case we are looking at wave solutions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ce^{i\omega(r-t)}+de^{-i\omega(r+t)}}{r}$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 term describes waves moving 
\emph on
out
\emph default
 towards 
\begin_inset Formula $r\to\infty$
\end_inset

, while the 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 term describes waves moving 
\emph on
in
\emph default
 from infinity.
 In wave problems, we typically impose a boundary condition of 
\emph on
outgoing waves at infinity
\emph default
, in which case we must set 
\begin_inset Formula $d=0$
\end_inset

.
 (However, the choice would have been reversed if we picked the opposite
 sign convention, 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{+i\omega t}$
\end_inset

, for the time dependence.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let's focus on 
\begin_inset Formula $g(r)=ce^{i\omega r}/r$
\end_inset

.
 As in class, the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r$
\end_inset

 singularity is no problem in 3d (it is cancelled by the Jacobian factor
 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}dr$
\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a regular distribution.
 Given an arbitrary test function 
\begin_inset Formula $q(\vec{x}),$
\end_inset

 we now evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\hat{A}g)\{q\} & =g\{\hat{A}q\}=\int g\hat{A}q\\
 & =\int_{0}^{\infty}r^{2}dr\int_{0}^{2\pi}d\phi\int_{0}^{\pi}\sin\theta\, d\theta\,\left[-\omega^{2}gq-\frac{g}{r}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial r^{2}}(rq)+\underbrace{\cancel{\left(\theta,\phi\mbox{ derivatives of }q\right)}}_{\mbox{integrate to 0, from class}}\right]\\
 & =\iint\sin\theta\, d\theta\, d\phi\left[\int_{0}^{\infty}c\left(-\omega^{2}rqe^{i\omega r}-\underbrace{e^{i\omega r}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial r^{2}}[rq]}_{\mbox{int. by parts}}\right)dr\right]\\
 & =\iint\sin\theta\, d\theta\, d\phi\left[\left.-ce^{i\omega r}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}[rq]\right|_{0}^{\infty}+c\int_{0}^{\infty}\left(-\omega^{2}rqe^{i\omega r}+\underbrace{i\omega e^{i\omega r}\frac{\partial}{\partial r}[rq]}_{\mbox{int. by parts}}\right)dr\right]\\
 & =\iint\sin\theta\, d\theta\, d\phi\left[cq(0)-\cancel{\left.ic\omega e^{i\omega r}[rq]\right|_{0}^{\infty}}+c\int_{0}^{\infty}\left(\cancel{-\omega^{2}rqe^{i\omega r}+\omega^{2}e^{i\omega r}[rq]}\right)dr\right]\\
 & =4\pi cq(0),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{c=1/4\pi}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=\frac{e^{i\omega|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|}}{4\pi|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|}
\]

\end_inset

assuming boundary conditions such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d=0$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, since exactly the same result applies to the 
\begin_inset Formula $de^{-i\omega r}/r$
\end_inset

 term, we obtain,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=\frac{ce^{i\omega|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|}+de^{-i\omega|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|}}{|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{c+d=1/4\pi}$
\end_inset

, with the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $c/d$
\end_inset

 being set by the boundary conditions at 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The value at 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}=\vec{x}'$
\end_inset

 being irrelevant in the distribution sense, e.g.
 we can assign it to zero, since this is a regular distribution with a finite
 integral, similar to class.)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
